<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAFETY OF BICYCLISTS IS TWO-WAY STREET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was interesting to read Richard Beene's column requesting motorists to be 
mindful of the safety and well-being of cyclists. The story also asks that 
cyclists ride safely and responsibly. 
</P>
<P>
All very applaudable, indeed. 
</P>
<P>
Now let's talk about cyclists' use of multiple-use pathways in Huntington 
Beach. An alarmingly large number of cyclists daily ignore posted speed limits 
(10 m.p.h. maximum, 5 m.p.h. when pedestrians are present). These offending 
cyclists ride at speeds of up to 20 m.p.h. and more, weaving between 
pedestrians and other cyclists. 
</P>
<P>
Last week I was struck from behind by a cyclist going 15 to 18 m.p.h., 
according to him. He wasn't watching where he was going. It still hurts. 
</P>
<P>
If cyclists want to go fast, then get out on the highway and take your chances 
with cars -- your 20 m.p.h. versus the car at 55 m.p.h. Don't be such cowards 
as to ride down a path of people on foot with your 20-m.p.h. dangerous speed, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
STEVEN D. ANDERSON 
</P>
<P>
Huntington Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
