<DOCID> 273781 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 9, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 7; Column 2; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
146 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLATFORM; 
</P>
<P>
WAR ON CITIZENS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Harvey Feldman is research director of the San Francisco-based YES Project 
(Youth Environment Study) and former consultant to the Drug Abuse Prevention 
Office of the Los Angeles County Department of Health Services. He commented on 
Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl F. Gates' statement calling for casual drug 
users to be shot: 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What in the world can you say to something like that? My first reaction is that 
it's hyperbole that comes out of Alice in Wonderland or as (marijuana 
researcher) Tod Mikuriya referred to it, "Malice in Blunderland." 
</P>
<P>
Over the years, drug policy has widened its net of who moves into the criminal 
category, so that more and more U.S. citizens are pulled into criminal 
sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
The question was what severity of criminal sanctions is going to produce the 
necessary result. 
</P>
<P>
What this one does for people who are not committed drug-users is to move them 
into criminal categories that (Gates) says are equal to treason. What it does 
is place the government at war with its citizens -- for the most part citizens 
not at war with their government. 
</P>
<P>
Their behavior for the most part is recreational and ought to be outside the 
whole scope of what is considered criminal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
