<HEADLINE>
<P>
Q &amp; A 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Q: I would greatly appreciate any information you can give me on Control Data 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
I've held this stock for several years because of information in the firm's 
annual report about reorganizations and other efforts to raise profitability. 
It is difficult for me to understand how the information in the annual report 
can be correct, while the company is not paying dividends and the price of the 
stock continues to fall. -- Jamestown, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
A: The headline of a recent Mabon, Nugent &amp; Co. report about Control Data 
is: "Like Watching Paint Dry." 
</P>
<P>
Charles Frumberg, the analyst who follows the computer company, admits that 
Control Data has been "a war of attrition for investors" who've been waiting 
for an upturn in earnings. But he thinks that good things are about to happen 
for all of you patient shareholders, so he is recommending that clients buy the 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
Frumberg says the firm's businesses are starting to improve, which might allow 
Control Data to embark on a restructuring that could come in the fourth 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
A restructuring, Frumberg predicts, could give Control Data stock a boost. 
</P>
<P>
But before the company can buy back some of its own stock as part of any 
restructuring, the analyst says, it will have to obtain some debt relief. It 
will probably also want to sell its 10 million shares of Seagate Technology. 
</P>
<P>
Frumberg thinks Control Data will earn $1.25 a share this year. That compares 
to a loss of more than $16 a share in 1989. The Institutional Brokers Estimate 
System at Lynch, Jones &amp; Ryan says the average estimate of all analysts who 
follow the company is $1.27 a share -- close to Frumberg's figure. The highest 
estimate is $1.50 a share, the lowest $1. 
</P>
<P>
Says Frumberg: "If someone was ever going to own this stock, now is the time to 
own it. The earnings are now becoming substantial, and a restructuring is 
imminent." 
</P>
<P>
Q: When World War II ended, I bought some Russian bonds that dated back to 
1916, 1919 and 1921. I paid 10 cents on the dollar. I'd like to know their 
value today. Will the new regime in Russia make good on the bonds, or do I have 
a better chance of winning the lottery? -- Newport Beach 
</P>
<P>
A: The bonds are probably worth zilch today. But there is hope. 
</P>
<P>
At the economic summit in Houston earlier this year, the United States 
disclosed that it was negotiating to resolve financial claims with Russia 
dating back to the czar. 
</P>
<P>
Britain struck such a deal in 1986. The Russians agreed to pay off czarist 
bonds that were repudiated after the 1917 Bolshevik revolution. Bondholders got 
about 10 cents on the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
But in the past few years, the Russians have coughed up more money, according 
to Robert Fisher, vice president of R. M. Smythe in New York. British holders 
of czarist bonds have now gotten back about one-third of what is owed them. 
</P>
<P>
Keep the faith. But it probably wouldn't hurt to play the lottery anyway. 
</P>
<P>
Q: While I was at an airport in Pittsburgh, I came across the enclosed brochure 
for a investment product handled by a firm called ELCOA. It claims to pay an 
effective annual rate of 10.58% on a six-month investment. Can you tell me more 
about this type of investment? What are the risks, and how secure is ELCOA? 
Venice, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
A: What ELCOA is doing is simple. 
</P>
<P>
ELCOA stands for Equipment Leasing Corp. of America. The company will take your 
investment and that of thousands of other people and buy equipment -- 
everything from fax machines to lathes -- which it then leases out. The ELCOA 
offering is handled by an investment firm called Welco Securities Inc. of Bala 
Cynwyd, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
The first thing I did was check out Welco. The National Assn. of Securities 
Dealers in Washington says it had a minor problem with the company in 1986, but 
otherwise it appears to be clean. 
</P>
<P>
I then spoke with a Welco salesman, without identifying myself as a reporter. 
He said the ELCOA fund invests one-third of its money in office equipment, 
one-third in light commercial equipment and the rest in restaurant equipment. 
He said defaults on its leases have been running at about 2.75% a year. 
</P>
<P>
The salesman pooh-poohed the idea that a recession could cause the default rate 
to skyrocket and the investment's return to plunge. "If you are talking 
depression, with thousands of businesses folding, then there's a risk," he 
finally conceded. 
</P>
<P>
But I wonder how many restaurants will be returning refrigerators, and how many 
office computers will be returned unpaid for if there is just a run-of-the-mill 
recession. You'll have to decide if this risk is worth the few extra dollars 
you'll earn on your money. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I have been trying to find out the value of two gold coins that I obtained 
from an estate, but have been unsuccessful. One is a 1901 $10 gold piece with 
an eagle, 13 stars and three arrows on the lower right. It is in perfect 
condition. The other is dated 1846 and is a $5 gold piece. It has three arrows 
in the lower right, 13 stars and an eagle. -- Tustin. 
</P>
<P>
A: The key phrase is "perfect condition." If the $10 piece is one of the few 
truly perfect ones -- in the numismatic sense of the word -- it could be worth 
"thousands of dollars," according to Norman Stack, partner of Stack's, a New 
York rare coin dealer. If it is less than perfect, it's worth between $250 and 
$500. 
</P>
<P>
The $5 piece is more common and worth around $150, he says. 
</P>
<P>
You should also check the coin for the city in which it was minted. The letters 
O for New Orleans, C for Charlotte, N.C., or D for Dahlonega, Ga., might 
appear. If there is no letter, it was minted in Philadelphia. The D, O and C 
markings would add to the coin's value. JOHN CRUDELE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
